Q7_fair_comment: Large costs on storage and personel involved. Same is also true for a decent Research data management plan

Q7_prereg_comment: Even though I personally understand how it will be beneficial, there is a lot of competition and fear of scooping in my field.
Q7_rr_comment:
Even though I personally understand how it will be beneficial, there is a lot of competition and fear of scooping in my field. The incentives for preregistration or registered report are low/none as things are at the moment, and they are often seen as a waste of time and a risk for being scooped. "Fast results" have higher rewards. I think adoption of these practices would have to come along with slow science for them to work in my field.
It is also true that in exploratory science it is very difficult to define the methods and exact steps/analysis until you get some data, so registered reports are also difficult to write.

Q6_material_comment: Raw data too large for public repositories, therefore only (if at all) deposition of processed data.

Q7_oa_comment:
This statement accounts for all of the above: If every of the above steps are implemented suddently a paper does not take 3 but 6 years, there is no staff at all to cope with all this administration; If one wants all this documentation, one rather goes to industry or does clinical trials.
It will bascially prevent partly an environemnt at Uni which lives from "trying something out to check if something works or not" etc, and one implemented, will benefit those who dont do it because they will be more fast in publishing.

Once people have long term and not short term contracts, and once people dont have a super high publication pressure (premium paper after 3-5 years of postdoc or you can forget your academic carreer), then people would have the time to implement all that beautiful admin and documentation like you would find in startups or clinical environments.

But before, people would just get crashed by the workload, as also hardly no PI cares about how well you documented but cares about how many results you have at the end of the day (they also have publication pressure...)
